%I A392746 #98 Apr 22 2026 18:44:51
%S A392746 268801,799459,838457,893513,1108927,1239389,1271209,1420763,1500313,
%T A392746 1719871,1751173,1940489,2349013,2435933,3092603,3197437,3380287,
%U A392746 3890519,4262101,4273193,4387181,4418047,4528309,4556039,4655867,4681811,4813693,4982053,5531663,5798783
%N A392746 Squarefree k with 4 distinct prime factors such that A010846(k) = A024718(4) = 50.
%C A392746 This sequence lists numbers with 4 distinct prime factors that have the least number of terms possible in row k of A162306. The smallest possible row length for k with 4 distinct prime factors is A024718(4) = 50.
%C A392746 Let primes p < q < r < s divide k.
%C A392746 The number k has the property that floor(log_p k) = omega(k) = 4 but floor(log_Q k) = omega(k)-1 for prime divisors Q > p, where omega = A001221.
%C A392746 This sequence is a proper subset of A383178; it includes k in A383178 such that k < p*r^3.
%C A392746 This sequence is analogous to A138109 and A383177, which instead pertain to squarefree k with 2 and 3 distinct prime factors, respectively.
%C A392746 a(1) = A384000(4).
%C A392746 Numbers m <= a(n) such that rad(m) | a(n) are products of p, q, r, and s raised to respective exponents listed in row 4 of A384001.
%H A392746 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A392746/b392746.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A392746 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="https://oeis.org/A383178/a383178.png">Hasse diagram of row a(1) of A162306</a> with logarithmic vertical scale. Gray represents 1, red represents primes, gold represents proper prime powers, green squarefree composites, blue numbers that are neither squarefree nor squareful, and magenta powerful numbers that are not prime powers.
%H A392746 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A392746/a392746.txt">Efficient Mathematica program</a>.
%e A392746 Let s = A383178.
%e A392746 Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..12:
%e A392746    n               a(n)   p *  q *  r *  s     p*r^3
%e A392746   --------------------------------------------------------------
%e A392746    1    s(2) =  268801 = 13 * 23 * 29 * 31 <  317057 = 13 * 29^3
%e A392746    2    s(8) =  799459 = 17 * 31 * 37 * 41 <  861101 = 17 * 37^3
%e A392746    3    s(9) =  838457 = 17 * 31 * 37 * 43 <  861101 = 17 * 37^3
%e A392746    4   s(10) =  893513 = 19 * 31 * 37 * 41 <  962407 = 19 * 37^3
%e A392746    5   s(12) = 1108927 = 17 * 37 * 41 * 43 < 1171657 = 17 * 41^3
%e A392746    6   s(14) = 1239389 = 19 * 37 * 41 * 43 < 1309499 = 19 * 41^3
%e A392746    7   s(15) = 1271209 = 17 * 37 * 43 * 47 < 1351619 = 17 * 43^3
%e A392746    8   s(19) = 1420763 = 19 * 37 * 43 * 47 < 1510633 = 19 * 43^3
%e A392746    9   s(20) = 1500313 = 23 * 37 * 41 * 43 < 1585183 = 23 * 41^3
%e A392746   10   s(26) = 1719871 = 23 * 37 * 43 * 47 < 1828661 = 23 * 43^3
%e A392746   11   s(27) = 1751173 = 19 * 37 * 47 * 53 < 1972637 = 19 * 47^3
%e A392746   12   s(34) = 1940489 = 19 * 41 * 47 * 53 < 1972637 = 19 * 47^3
%e A392746 .
%e A392746 s(1) = 81719 = 11 * 17 * 19 * 23 is not a term since 11*19^3 = 75449 is in row s(1) of A162306, therefore A010846(s(1)) > 50.
%e A392746 s(3) = 565471 = 17 * 29 * 31 * 37 is not a term since 17*31^3 = 506447 is less than s(3), etc.
%t A392746 s = Select[Select[Range[2^21], SquareFreeQ], PrimeNu[#] == 4 &]; Select[s, Function[k, And[Floor@ Log[#1, k] == 4, Floor@ Log[#2, k] == 3, k < #1*#3^3] & @@ FactorInteger[k][[All, 1]] ] ]
%Y A392746 Cf. A010846, A024718, A138109, A162306, A383177, A383178, A384000, A384001.
%K A392746 nonn,new
%O A392746 1,1
%A A392746 _Michael De Vlieger_, Apr 10 2026
